faq:
  - q: "How do I calculate how much topsoil I need?"
    a: "Multiply the length and width of the area to get square feet, then multiply by desired depth. This calculator converts the result into cubic feet, cubic yards, bags, and cost."
  - q: "How deep should topsoil be for a lawn?"
    a: "For topdressing, a thin layer may be enough. For new lawns or filling low spots, you may need several inches depending on the condition of the existing soil."
  - q: "How many cubic feet are in a cubic yard of topsoil?"
    a: "There are 27 cubic feet in one cubic yard. Bulk topsoil is often sold by the cubic yard."
  - q: "How many bags of topsoil are in a cubic yard?"
    a: "It depends on bag size. For example, one-cubic-foot bags require 27 bags per cubic yard, while 1.5-cubic-foot bags require 18 bags per cubic yard."
  - q: "Should I add extra topsoil for settling?"
    a: "Yes. Soil can settle after rain, watering, and compaction. A small overage helps reduce the chance of coming up short."
  - q: "Is topsoil the same as garden soil?"
    a: "Not always. Topsoil is general surface soil, while garden soil may include added organic matter or amendments. Product quality and ingredients vary."
  - q: "Is bulk topsoil cheaper than bagged topsoil?"
    a: "Bulk topsoil is often more economical for large areas. Bagged topsoil is convenient for small repairs, small beds, and projects without delivery access."
  - q: "Can I spread topsoil over existing grass?"
    a: "A light topdressing can be spread over grass, but deep layers may smother existing turf. For lawn repair, keep the layer appropriate for your goal."
  - q: "How much topsoil do I need to level a yard?"
    a: "That depends on the area and average fill depth. Measure several low spots and use an average depth for a planning estimate."
  - q: "Should I screen topsoil before using it?"
    a: "Screened topsoil is often easier to spread and may contain fewer rocks, clumps, and debris. It can be useful for lawns and finished landscape areas."
